ntinued to be experienced and feared, both as a lived and constant spectral presence. It also examines how hunger was increasingly used as a disciplining device in new modes of governing the population. Drawing upon a rich archive, this innovative and conceptually-sophisticated study throws new light on how hunger persisted as a political and biological force.This book is relevant to United Nations Sustainable Development Goal 2, Zero hunger.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHungerzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aHungerzEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aPovertyzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aPovertyzEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aEighteenth century.  aEngland.  aFood riots.  aHunger.  aNineteenth century.  aProtest.  aRural.  aSocial policy.  aSpeenhamland.  aWorkhouse.  aZero hunger.1 aGriffin, Carl J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614563540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526145635423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526145635/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles